    title: "Acute Coronary Syndrome in the ICU",
    cellular: { title: "ACS Pathophysiology", content: "Acute coronary syndrome encompasses unstable angina, NSTEMI, and STEMI, all resulting from disruption of atherosclerotic plaque in coronary arteries. Plaque rupture exposes the thrombogenic lipid core and collagen to circulating platelets and clotting factors, triggering thrombus formation. Complete occlusion produces STEMI with transmural ischemia, while partial occlusion causes NSTEMI or unstable angina with subendocardial ischemia. At the cellular level, ischemic myocytes switch to anaerobic glycolysis within seconds, depleting ATP. Without ATP, calcium homeostasis fails, causing myofibrillar hypercontraction and eventual necrosis. The ischemic cascade produces characteristic biomarker release: troponin I/T from damaged myofibrils peaks at 12-24 hours, CK-MB from mitochondria peaks at 24 hours. Reperfusion injury paradoxically worsens damage through reactive oxygen species generation and calcium overload." },
